Some definitions

In parasitology, a definitive host is an organism that harbors a parasite that has reached sexual maturity. An intermediate host is an organism that harbors a parasite that has not yet reached sexual maturity. - Bard

#insect-vector #lymphadenopathy
About a week after the bite, the patient develops a chancre at the site of the bite.
Other syptoms are lymphadenopathy (painless, posterior chain) and hepatosplenomegaly.

P Falciparum => No relapses from liver! FALCIPARUM DOES NOT FORM HYPNOZOITES!
In P Ovale, all stages of the life cycle are seen in the blood film whereas in P. falciparum only trophozoites and gametocytes are seen in the blood. (therfore, if all forms are seen, chloroquine can be given. )
Films should be repeated every 8 - 12 hours if malaria is suspected.
If ACT is unavailable and if local falciparum is sensitive to chloroquine-> then chloroquine can be used.
South asian P. Vivax is resistant to chloroquine (?sensntive in other regions) -> Give ACT for vivax infections.
Primaquine reduces transmisibility. Main action is to eradicate hyponozoites. Also acts against gametocytes but has no effect against asexual blood stages.
Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (symptoms occur due to viral reactivation in teenage years) and post measles encephalomyeltis (2 weeks after infection) are dreaded complications.

Cyclospora cayatensis infection

Protozoan
Obligate human parasite (Humans are only known host)
Ingestion of sporulated oocyst from fruits / vegetables / water -> infection -> infection of GI mucosa
Low grade fever with anorexia, nausea, flatus, diarrhoea (symptoms can be chronic)
Direct faeco oral transmission is not possible as defecated unsporulated oocyst must mature for days / weeks in the environment.
Treatment: trimethoprim sulfamethoxazole.

Schistosoma

[!TIP] Patient goes swimming in fresh water and then presents with haematuria or diarrhoea. NOT A gastrointestinally acquired pathogen.

Parasitic infection by a trematode (Phylum platyhelminthes)
Complex life cycle : snails -> intermediate host; human -> definitive host.
3 or 4 Species of parasites.

After skin penetration they worms migrate to the liver. Then, one species lays eggs in the paravesical venous plexus -> eggs migrate to bladder -> haematuria
The two others lay eggs in the mesenteric veins -> eggs migrate to intestinal lumen -> diarrhoea
Infective stages are excreted via urine and faeces.

Acute infection : seen in travellers; locals can have low level parasitaemia
Acute infection can present with "swimmer's itch" (acute itch after swimming + localized dermatitis - when parasite enters the skin) and/or acute schistosomiasis syndrome (Katayama syndrome), a systemic hypersensitivity reaction to schistosome antigens and circulating immune complexes. (See 'Acute infection' above.)

Chronic infection - GI - GI ulceration and scarring + blood loss; liver fibrosis and oesophageal varices .
Diagnosis : urine culture and microscopy

Treatment: Praziquantel - antihelminthic drug and steroids to reduce inflammation.

Leishmaniasis

[!TIP] Typhus => Fever, lymphadenopathy, lymphopenia, thrombocytopenia, ESCHAR,
Typhus involves the lyphoid system -> atypical lymphocytes, lymphadenopathy, lymphopenia etc
Suspect with Fever + tender lymphadenopathy + travel history -> then FBC will show lymphopenia, hypoalbuminaemia, atypical lymphocytes

  • Lymphadenopathy - regional or generalized tender lymphadenopathy
  • Pneumonitis or encephalitis, Central nervous system (CNS), pulmonary, or cardiac involvement, Rarely, acute renal failure, shock, and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) - potentially fatal disease
    Transmitted via larval tick bite. (trombiculid mites)
    Pathogen: Bacterium - Orientia tsutsugamushi - Obligate intracellular pathogen, belongs to ricketsia
  • Early lymphopenia with late lymphocytosis + atypical lymphocytes in blood pic.
